re, England, United Kingdom","Oare, Wiltshire, England":"Oare, Wiltshire, England","Wilcot, Wiltshire, England":"Wilcot, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gitton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>gitoun</i> ‘military or guild banner’ (Anglo-Norman French  <i>guidon</i>), though the post-medieval bearers may belong to (2).","2  Welsh:  see  Gethin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gitting","meanings":["Welsh, English: variant of   Gethin   or   Gitton  .  Compare  Gitten  ."]},{"name":"Gethin","meanings":["(1997: 18;2007: 39; 2010: NA)","Welsh: from the personal name <i>Gethin</i>, perhaps a soft-mutated form of <i>cethin</i> ‘dusky, swarthy’."]},{"name":"Gethins","meanings":["1  Welsh, English, Scottish: (i) variant of   Gethin  , with English genitival or excrescent  <i>-s</i>. (ii) possibly also a variant of   Gitton   (1) with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>.","2  Irish: if not the Welsh name in Ireland, this name may have been adopted as a shortened form of  <b>Mag Eiteagáin</b>,  see  McGettigan  ."]},{"name":"Gitten","meanings":["Welsh, English: variant of   Gethin   or   Gitton  .  Compare  Gitting  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Gitton was born about 1430, in Oare, Wiltshire, England, his father, William Gitton, was 22 and his mother, Mrs. William Gitton, was 17. He married Cecily Axtell about 1455, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1490, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"about 1430–about 1490":"umbes 1430–umbes 1490","1430–1490":"1430–1490","1435–1495":"1435–1495","1455–1514":"1455–1514","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1414–Female":"1414–Surnud","1514":"1514","1414":"1414","1435":"1435","about 1490":"umbes 1490","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","about 1455":"umbes 1455","1495":"1495","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1490":"1490","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Oare, Wiltshire, England":"Oare, Wiltshire, England","Wilcot, Wiltshire, England":"Wilcot, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1430–about 1490":"noin 1430–noin 1490","1430–1490":"1430–1490","1435–1495":"1435–1495","1455–1514":"1455–1514","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1414–Female":"1414–Kuollut","1514":"1514","1414":"1414","1435":"1435","about 1490":"noin 1490","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","about 1455":"noin 1455","1495":"1495","about 1430":"noin 1430","1490":"1490","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Oare, Wiltshire, England":"Oare, Wilt